# fedora — distro primer
#
# fedora is the upstream feeder for RHEL: a 6-month-cadence point-release
# distro maintained by Red Hat with heavy community involvement. each
# release is supported for ~13 months (current + previous), so you upgrade
# roughly once a year and have a 1-month grace window. fedora 44 (current)
# is supported through May 2026.
#
# default stack on a fresh Workstation install:
#
#   - GNOME on Wayland (Plasma + others are official Spins)
#   - btrfs root (since F33), with @ / @home subvolumes inside; ext4 still
#     an option in anaconda for those who pick it
#   - LUKS root encryption offered in the installer (off by default on
#     Workstation; some derivatives default to on)
#   - systemd everywhere
#   - NetworkManager
#   - firewalld (zone-based; FedoraWorkstation zone by default)
#   - SELinux ENFORCING (don't disable it; targeted policy is fine)
#   - PipeWire for audio (replaced pulseaudio as default)
#   - dnf5 from Fedora 41 onwards (native C++ rewrite of dnf4 — see [[dnf]])
#   - GRUB2 + BootLoaderSpec (per-kernel .conf files in /boot/loader/entries/)
#
# editions worth knowing:
#
#   - Workstation       — GNOME desktop. the default
#   - KDE Spin / Plasma — official KDE edition (promoted to Edition in F42)
#   - Server            — text-mode + cockpit web UI; xfs root (not btrfs)
#   - Silverblue        — immutable Workstation, rpm-ostree atomic updates
#   - Kinoite           — immutable KDE, same model as Silverblue
#   - Sericea / Onyx    — immutable Sway / Budgie
#   - CoreOS            — minimal, auto-updating, container-host focused
#   - IoT               — ostree-based, ARM/x86 for edge devices
#   - Spins             — XFCE, MATE, Cinnamon, LXQt, i3, etc.
#   - Labs              — purpose-built bundles (Astronomy, Robotics,
#                         Comp Neuro, Design Suite, ...)


RELEASE / UPGRADE
-----------------

# fedora is point-release. you upgrade in place between versions with the
# system-upgrade plugin (the supported path — DON'T just edit /etc/dnf/dnf.conf
# and `dnf upgrade` your way across, that's the partial-upgrade trap).

# refresh, install the plugin (already shipped on F41+), and pull the new
# release's packages WITHOUT applying them:
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo dnf install dnf5-plugin-system-upgrade        # F41+; on F40 it's dnf-plugin-system-upgrade
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=45   # pick the target release

# stage the actual upgrade — reboots into a special target that performs
# the rpm transactions, then reboots again into the new system
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot

# what to do BEFORE the system-upgrade:
#   - merge .rpmnew / .rpmsave files in /etc:
sudo find /etc -name '*.rpmnew' -o -name '*.rpmsave'
#   - check release notes for known breakage:
#       fedoraproject.org/wiki/Releases/<n>/ChangeSet
#       discussion.fedoraproject.org (Common Issues thread)
#   - snapshot if you're on btrfs and have snapper / timeshift configured

# check current release:
cat /etc/fedora-release
rpm -E %fedora                                      # just the number

# remember: skipping releases is supported (F43 → F45) but not RECOMMENDED.
# the more versions you cross the more likely some package combination
# trips the resolver. one hop at a time is the safe path.


UPGRADE STRATEGY — STAYING SUPPORTED WITHOUT DAY-ZERO PAIN
----------------------------------------------------------

# fedora's release math gives you a wide window:
#   - 2 releases / year (~April and ~October)
#   - ~13 months of support per release
#   - so N-1 stays supported for ~7 months AFTER N releases (generous
#     overlap — use it)
#   - hard deadline: don't sit on a release once N+2 is announced. that's
#     when the EOL clock starts ticking hard.
#
# day-zero upgrades are voluntary risk. the only thing you actually
# HAVE to avoid is going EOL.


# THE T+8 RULE (recommended default)

# wait 8 weeks after a release before upgrading. by T+8:
#   - 1-2 kernel point releases have shipped (6.x.1, 6.x.2)
#   - DE patch releases (GNOME 47.1 instead of .0) have landed
#   - the worst third-party-repo lag has resolved
#   - the Common Issues thread has stabilized
#
# you give up ~2 months on the bleeding edge. you gain dramatically
# fewer "why did my system break" incidents.


# CALENDAR IN PRACTICE
#
#   fall release (~Oct/Nov)     →  upgrade in January   (past holidays,
#                                                        T+8-10 weeks)
#   spring release (~April/May) →  upgrade in June/July (T+8-10 weeks)
#
# this puts you on every release ~2 months after launch, ALWAYS one
# release ahead of EOL, never racing the clock.


# 5-POINT PRE-UPGRADE SANITY CHECK
# (run at T+8 weeks; if any item is red, wait 4 more and re-check)

# a) Common Issues thread is quiet for your stack:
#       https://discussion.fedoraproject.org/c/announcements/

# b) RPM Fusion ships for fedora N:
curl -sI https://download1.rpmfusion.org/free/fedora/releases/45/Everything/x86_64/os/

# c) akmod-nvidia is built for fedora N (only if you use nvidia — this
#    is the #1 cause of "I'm on a black screen after upgrade"):
dnf --releasever=45 list akmod-nvidia 2>/dev/null

# d) your critical COPRs have published for fedora N. check each at
#    copr.fedoraproject.org/coprs/

# e) your current install is healthy:
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo find /etc -name '*.rpmnew' -o -name '*.rpmsave'
sudo reboot                                    # confirm clean boot first


# UPGRADE — THE COMMAND SEQUENCE
# (only after the sanity check is green)

# 1. snapshot first — btrfs root + a manual snapshot gives you a
#    rollback path:
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot / /.snapshot-pre-f45

# 2. system-upgrade plugin + download:
sudo dnf install dnf5-plugin-system-upgrade
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=45

# 3. apply (reboots into a special target, performs the rpm
#    transactions, reboots again into the new release):
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot

# 4. verify post-upgrade. smoke test the things you actually use:
cat /etc/fedora-release                        # confirm version
lsmod | grep nvidia                            # if applicable
nvidia-smi                                     # if applicable
# launch your terminal, browser, dev toolchain, any niche apps.


# ROLLBACK IF SOMETHING BROKE

# btrfs rollback path (assumes you took the snapshot in step 1):
sudo btrfs subvolume set-default \
    $(sudo btrfs subvolume list / | grep '.snapshot-pre-f45' | awk '{print $2}') /
sudo reboot
# you're back on the pre-upgrade subvolume. promote it back to default
# permanently via `btrfs subvolume set-default` or by mounting the
# old @ and copying it back. this is exactly the openSUSE / Manjaro
# snapshot-rollback story, just hand-rolled instead of snapper-driven.


# SEQUENTIAL > SKIPPING

# fedora SUPPORTS skipping releases (N-2 → N) via:
#       sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=N
# but the rpm resolver gets exponentially crankier with each version
# crossed. ALWAYS upgrade sequentially:
#       N → N+1 → N+2
# one extra hour, dramatically less --allowerasing debugging.
#
# if you've been off the grid and woke up on N-2:
sudo dnf system-upgrade download --releasever=$(( $(rpm -E %fedora) + 1 ))
sudo dnf system-upgrade reboot
# boot, verify, reboot to a clean state, repeat for the next hop.


# PRE-UPGRADE HARD RULES (apply to every upgrade)

# - DON'T upgrade with un-merged .rpmnew files. they carry forward and
#   bite you later. merge them on current release first.
# - DON'T upgrade from a non-default kernel. boot the standard
#   /boot/vmlinuz-<latest> first.
# - DON'T upgrade with a broken current install. fix the current release
#   first — dnf system-upgrade is not a recovery tool.
# - DISABLE third-party repos that don't ship for N yet (chrome COPRs,
#   vendor repos, etc.). re-enable after.
# - On nvidia: CONFIRM akmod-nvidia has shipped for fedora N before
#   pulling the trigger. (sanity check c above.)


# WHERE TO MONITOR

# - discussion.fedoraproject.org/c/announcements/  — official notes,
#   Common Issues per release. this is the canonical source.
# - fedoramagazine.org                             — readable summaries
# - bodhi.fedoraproject.org                        — see what's in
#   updates-testing if you want to peek ahead
# - fedoraproject.org/wiki/Releases/N/ChangeSet    — per-release
#   major changes
#
# RSS-subscribe at least the first two. the rest you check at upgrade
# time.


# WHAT THIS STRATEGY EXPLICITLY ACCEPTS

# - ~2 months behind early adopters on new features.
# - never bleeding-edge, never EOL — a permanent middle lane.
# - ~1 hour of effort every 6 months (sanity check + upgrade).
# - snapshot rollback path means worst-case recovery is minutes,
#   not a reinstall.


BACKUPS — SNAPSHOTS ARE NOT BACKUPS
-----------------------------------

# the most-skipped section of any setup primer, and the one that
# matters most the first time something goes wrong. before any tools:
# get the mental model right.


# THE MENTAL MODEL — WHY SNAPSHOTS DON'T COUNT

# btrfs snapshots (covered in UPGRADE STRATEGY) protect you against
# a software-level mistake: a bad upgrade, an `rm -rf` you ran in the
# wrong directory and noticed within hours. they DO NOT protect you
# against:
#   - the disk physically failing (snapshot and original on same disk)
#   - the controller eating the filesystem (same fs)
#   - ransomware encrypting your files (snapshot can be deleted too)
#   - theft / fire (the laptop is gone)
#   - a sync mistake that propagates the delete to the snapshot
#
# the 3-2-1 rule, modernized: 3 copies of your data, on 2 different
# storage technologies, with 1 of them PHYSICALLY OFFSITE. snapshots
# count as zero of those.


# WHAT TO BACK UP

# CRITICAL (irreplaceable):
#   - ~/.gnupg, ~/.ssh — losing these is recovery hell
#   - ~/.local/share/keyrings, ~/.config/{1Password,bitwarden} — passwords
#   - your /home in general — documents, projects, browser profiles
#   - /etc — your edited configs (small but precious)
#   - /var/lib/<service> for anything you self-host (postgres, mysql,
#     docker / podman volumes, gitea, nextcloud...)
#   - the "user-installed package" list (treat as a regenerator, not data):
sudo dnf repoquery --userinstalled --queryformat '%{name}\n' \
    | sort > ~/backup-userinstalled.txt
flatpak list --columns=application > ~/backup-flatpaks.txt

# REGENERATABLE (skip):
#   - /var/cache, /tmp, /var/tmp
#   - ~/.cache
#   - container images (re-pull)
#   - build artifacts (target/, node_modules/, .venv/, __pycache__/)
#   - /usr, /boot — package manager rebuilds these


# TOOLS — IN ORDER OF SOPHISTICATION

# 1. RSYNC — the foundation. simple, reliable. NOT a backup tool on its
#    own because it has no versioning — if you sync after a `rm -rf`
#    you've propagated the disaster. fine for "copy /home to USB" once.
rsync -aHAX --delete /home/ /run/media/$USER/backup/home/

# 2. BTRFS SEND / RECEIVE — incremental cross-machine snapshot
#    transfer. zero parsing of files, exact, fast. requires btrfs on
#    BOTH ends. great for "back up snapshots to a NAS over ssh".
#    see [[btrfs]] SEND / RECEIVE section.

# 3. BORG (borgbackup) — the most-recommended Linux backup tool.
#    deduplicated, encrypted, compressed. CLI-driven, mature.
#    repository can be local, USB, or remote over SSH. mountable for
#    browsing past states.
sudo dnf install borgbackup
borg init --encryption=repokey-blake2 /run/media/$USER/borg-repo
borg create --stats --compression zstd,3 \
    /run/media/$USER/borg-repo::"home-$(date +%F)" \
    /home/$USER \
    --exclude='/home/*/.cache' \
    --exclude='/home/*/.local/share/Trash' \
    --exclude='**/node_modules' \
    --exclude='**/target' \
    --exclude='**/.venv'
borg list /run/media/$USER/borg-repo                    # past archives
borg mount /run/media/$USER/borg-repo::home-2026-06-14 /mnt/r
borg prune --keep-daily 7 --keep-weekly 4 --keep-monthly 12 \
    /run/media/$USER/borg-repo
borg compact /run/media/$USER/borg-repo                 # reclaim space

# 4. RESTIC — borg's newer rival. similar feature set, written in go,
#    crucial difference: native support for many cloud backends
#    (S3, B2, Wasabi, Azure, GCS, OneDrive, SFTP, rclone) without
#    wrappers. pick this if you want cloud-native backups.
sudo dnf install restic
export RESTIC_REPOSITORY="b2:my-bucket:fedora-backup"
export RESTIC_PASSWORD_FILE="$HOME/.restic-password"
restic init
restic backup /home/$USER \
    --exclude="$HOME/.cache" \
    --exclude="**/node_modules" \
    --exclude="**/target"
restic snapshots
restic mount /mnt/r
restic forget --keep-daily 7 --keep-weekly 4 --keep-monthly 12 --prune

# 5. DEJA-DUP (gnome backups GUI) — wraps duplicity. easy "back up
#    /home to external drive" for non-CLI users. less capable than
#    borg/restic. ships in fedora workstation:
sudo dnf install deja-dup


# DESTINATIONS — THE 3-2-1 BREAKDOWN

# COPY 1 — your live filesystem on the laptop (doesn't count as a
#          backup; it's the original).
#
# COPY 2 — local fast storage. external USB SSD, internal second drive,
#          or NAS on the LAN. fast restore, easy to verify, cheap.
#          weak point: same physical location as the original.
#
# COPY 3 — offsite. options in 2026:
#   - cloud object storage: backblaze B2 (~$5/TB/mo), wasabi, S3,
#     hetzner storage box (european-priced)
#   - rsync.net (SSH-accessible, borg-friendly, $1.50/TB/mo at scale,
#     popular with borg users)
#   - friend's house with a NAS, swap drives quarterly
#   - work backup if your employer allows it (check policy)
#
# the offsite copy is what saves you from fire, theft, and ransomware.
# don't skip it.


# ENCRYPTION & KEY MANAGEMENT — THE WHOLE GAME

# borg and restic encrypt by default. that's good. but:
#
#   - LOSING THE PASSPHRASE = BACKUPS GONE. no recovery, no support
#     desk, no "i forgot my password" link.
#   - don't store the passphrase in ~/.config/borg/passwd on the same
#     machine you're backing up. obvious chicken-and-egg.
#
# acceptable passphrase-storage strategies:
#   - print it, store in a fire safe at home + a duplicate at a
#     trusted location (parents' house, safety deposit box)
#   - put it in a password manager whose vault you can recover via
#     a different path (e.g. 1Password / Bitwarden recovery key
#     printed and stored physically)
#   - cryptsetup luksHeaderBackup-style: a small file you keep on
#     multiple USB sticks geographically separated


# RECOMMENDED SETUP FOR A DAILY DRIVER

# a layered approach that won't burn you:
#
#   - btrfs snapshots BEFORE every -Syu via timeshift or manual
#     (rolling-release safety net; see UPGRADE STRATEGY)
#   - borg or restic to a LOCAL external SSD, WEEKLY (fast restore,
#     cheap)
#   - restic to a CLOUD backend (B2 or rsync.net), NIGHTLY
#     (the offsite leg)
#   - QUARTERLY restore drill: actually pull one file back from cloud
#     to confirm the backup works


# AUTOMATION — SYSTEMD TIMERS, NOT CRON

# don't use cron for backups on fedora. systemd timers integrate with
# the journal (you can see failures with journalctl), respect
# OnFailure= for notification hooks, and survive reboots cleanly.

# example: nightly restic backup as a user service.

mkdir -p ~/.config/systemd/user
cat >~/.config/systemd/user/restic-backup.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Nightly restic backup to B2

[Service]
Type=oneshot
Environment="RESTIC_REPOSITORY=b2:my-bucket:fedora-backup"
EnvironmentFile=%h/.config/restic/env
ExecStart=/usr/bin/restic backup %h --exclude=%h/.cache
ExecStart=/usr/bin/restic forget --keep-daily 7 --keep-weekly 4 --keep-monthly 12 --prune
EOF

cat >~/.config/systemd/user/restic-backup.timer <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Nightly restic backup

[Timer]
OnCalendar=*-*-* 02:30:00
Persistent=true
RandomizedDelaySec=900

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target
EOF

systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now restic-backup.timer
systemctl --user list-timers
# verify it ran:
journalctl --user -u restic-backup.service -n 50

# user services don't run when you're logged out unless lingering
# is enabled. for a laptop that's usually fine; for a desktop that
# runs unattended:
loginctl enable-linger "$USER"


# THE QUARTERLY RESTORE DRILL

# untested backups are not backups. once a quarter:
#
#   1. pick a file you care about from the last week
#   2. restore it from your CLOUD backup (not the local SSD — the
#      cloud copy is the one whose health matters most)
#   3. diff against the live version. confirm contents identical.
#   4. for bonus points: do a full restore to a VM, confirm boot
#
# 90% of "my backups don't work" stories are from people who never
# tested.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. DATABASES NEED DUMPS, NOT FILE-LEVEL BACKUPS. backing up a live
#    postgres data directory often produces unrestorable garbage.
#    dump first, then back up the dump:
sudo -u postgres pg_dumpall -f /backup/postgres-dump.sql
#    same for mysql (mysqldump), influxdb (influxd backup), etc.
#
# 2. ACTIVE VMs — shut down before file-level backup, or use libvirt
#    snapshot capture (see VIRTUAL MACHINES section).
#
# 3. DOCKER / PODMAN VOLUMES live under /var/lib/<engine>/. for
#    podman, `podman volume export` produces a tarball you can back up.
#
# 4. BACKING UP /home INCLUDES BROWSER PROFILES. firefox / chrome
#    while RUNNING hold open SQLite files — back up while the
#    browser is closed, or accept some files will be corrupt-at-rest
#    in the backup (recoverable via journal but not pretty).
#
# 5. DON'T BACK UP YOUR PASSWORD MANAGER VAULT TO A CLOUD YOU NEED
#    THE PASSWORD MANAGER TO ACCESS. circular. keep at least one
#    out-of-band copy.
#
# 6. SNAP'S AUTO-REFRESH WILL CHANGE FILES MID-BACKUP. not a fedora
#    problem but worth knowing if you have any snaps (you shouldn't
#    on fedora; this is one of the reasons people leave ubuntu —
#    see WHY UBUNTU USERS MIGRATE section).
#
# 7. RSYNC --DELETE WILL PROPAGATE ACCIDENTAL DELETIONS. if you use
#    rsync as your "backup" you have no protection against `rm -rf`.
#    this is exactly why borg / restic are real backup tools and
#    rsync isn't.


# IF YOU NEED ONE LINE OF GUIDANCE
#
#   `sudo dnf install restic` → point it at backblaze B2 → systemd
#   timer at 02:30 nightly → print the passphrase → put it in a safe.
#
# that's a real backup. everything else is optimization.


SYSTEMD — THE FOUNDATIONAL GLUE
-------------------------------

# fedora is the systemd REFERENCE platform — it's where systemd is
# tested first and adopted earliest. nearly every operational task on
# fedora goes through it: services, schedules, log access, mount
# management, boot, suspend, lid handling. this section is the
# minimum mental model + daily commands.


# MENTAL MODEL

# everything systemd does is modeled as a UNIT. unit TYPES are
# distinguished by file suffix:
#
#   .service   — a process (daemon, oneshot script, etc.)
#   .timer     — a schedule that activates another unit
#   .socket    — a socket that starts a service on connect
#   .mount     — a filesystem mount point
#   .automount — auto-mount on access
#   .target    — a grouping of other units (analogous to runlevels)
#   .path      — a filesystem-watching trigger
#   .slice     — a cgroup branch (resource limits)
#   .scope     — externally-launched processes adopted into a cgroup
#
# units have a DEPENDENCY GRAPH (After=, Wants=, Requires=, etc.) and
# systemd parallelizes startup based on it. boot is "reach
# default.target via its dependency tree."
#
# there are TWO instances on every system:
#
#   SYSTEM instance (--system, the default for `systemctl ...`)
#       runs as PID 1. shared resources, network, daemons.
#   USER instance (--user, per-login-user)
#       runs as your user. background apps, user services / timers.
#       no sudo. config in ~/.config/systemd/user/.


# SYSTEMCTL — DAILY COMMANDS

# status of a service
systemctl status sshd                       # current state + last logs
systemctl is-active sshd                    # one-word answer
systemctl is-enabled sshd                   # will it start at boot?
systemctl is-failed sshd

# lifecycle
sudo systemctl start sshd
sudo systemctl stop sshd
sudo systemctl restart sshd
sudo systemctl reload sshd                  # reload config, don't restart
sudo systemctl enable sshd                  # start at boot
sudo systemctl enable --now sshd            # enable AND start now
sudo systemctl disable sshd

# mask (refuse to start, even by dep) — heavier than disable
sudo systemctl mask suspend.target          # disable suspend entirely
sudo systemctl unmask suspend.target

# listing
systemctl                                   # every active unit
systemctl list-units --type=service
systemctl list-units --state=failed         # what's currently broken
systemctl list-unit-files                   # every unit FILE (not just active)
systemctl list-unit-files --state=enabled

# inspect dependencies
systemctl list-dependencies sshd            # what sshd needs
systemctl list-dependencies sshd --reverse  # what needs sshd
systemctl show sshd                         # every property

# reload systemd's view of unit files (after editing them)
sudo systemctl daemon-reload


# JOURNALCTL — LOG ACCESS

# fedora ships systemd-journald as the canonical log destination.
# /var/log/journal/ is persistent across reboots by default on F44.

# basics
journalctl                                  # all logs, paged
journalctl -e                               # jump to end
journalctl -f                               # follow (like tail -f)
journalctl --since "2 hours ago"
journalctl --since today
journalctl --until "2026-06-16 14:00"

# scoped to a unit (the most-used form)
journalctl -u sshd                          # all sshd logs
journalctl -u sshd -f                       # follow sshd
journalctl -u sshd --since today -p err     # only errors

# scoped to a boot
journalctl -b                               # current boot
journalctl -b -1                            # previous boot
journalctl --list-boots                     # what boot IDs exist

# user-instance logs (for ~/.config/systemd/user/ services)
journalctl --user -u my-app

# priority filter (0=emerg .. 7=debug)
journalctl -p warning..err                  # warning OR err
journalctl -p err -b                        # errors this boot

# pid / command-line filters (less-known, very useful)
journalctl _PID=1234
journalctl _COMM=sshd
journalctl _UID=1000

# output format
journalctl -u sshd -o cat                   # raw messages only
journalctl -u sshd -o json                  # full structured output
journalctl -u sshd -o short-iso             # ISO timestamps

# disk usage / rotation
journalctl --disk-usage
sudo journalctl --vacuum-time=2weeks        # delete entries older than
sudo journalctl --vacuum-size=2G            # cap journal at 2 GiB


# WRITING A SERVICE FILE

# system service (root-owned daemon). path: /etc/systemd/system/foo.service
sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/myapp.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=My App
After=network-online.target
Wants=network-online.target

[Service]
Type=simple                                 # most apps
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/myapp --port 8080
ExecReload=/bin/kill -HUP $MAINPID
Restart=on-failure
RestartSec=5
User=myapp                                  # run as a dedicated user
Group=myapp

# security hardening — apply unless you have a reason not to
NoNewPrivileges=yes
ProtectSystem=strict
ProtectHome=yes
PrivateTmp=yes
PrivateDevices=yes
ProtectKernelTunables=yes
ProtectKernelModules=yes
ProtectControlGroups=yes
RestrictSUIDSGID=yes
LockPersonality=yes

# write paths the service NEEDS access to (carve out from ProtectSystem)
ReadWritePaths=/var/lib/myapp

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
EOF

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable --now myapp.service
journalctl -u myapp -f

# Type= values worth knowing:
#   simple     — process is the daemon (no daemonize step)
#   exec       — like simple but waits until exec() succeeds
#   forking    — old-school: parent forks, child is the daemon
#   oneshot    — run, exit, that's normal. used with timers.
#   notify     — daemon notifies systemd when it's ready (sd_notify)

# USER SERVICE (no root needed, runs as you):
mkdir -p ~/.config/systemd/user
cat >~/.config/systemd/user/myapp.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=My user app

[Service]
ExecStart=%h/bin/myapp                       # %h = $HOME
Restart=on-failure

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
EOF
systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now myapp.service


# WRITING A TIMER

# timers fire .service units on a schedule. they are the systemd
# replacement for cron. ALWAYS paired: a foo.timer plus a foo.service.

cat >~/.config/systemd/user/cleanup.service <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Cleanup task

[Service]
Type=oneshot
ExecStart=/usr/bin/find %h/Downloads -mtime +30 -delete
EOF

cat >~/.config/systemd/user/cleanup.timer <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=Weekly cleanup

[Timer]
OnCalendar=Sun 03:00                        # every sunday at 3am
Persistent=true                             # catch up if missed
RandomizedDelaySec=600                      # 0-10min jitter

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target
EOF

systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now cleanup.timer

# list / debug timers
systemctl --user list-timers                # next + last fire times
systemctl --user status cleanup.timer

# OnCalendar syntax — the most common forms:
#   *-*-* 03:30:00      — every day at 03:30
#   Mon..Fri 09:00      — weekdays at 9am
#   *-*-01 00:00:00     — first of every month at midnight
#   hourly / daily / weekly / monthly       — convenient aliases
#   minutely / *:0/15   — every 15 minutes


# LINGER — USER SERVICES WITHOUT BEING LOGGED IN

# user services and timers only run while you're logged in. for a
# laptop that's usually fine. for a desktop or server, enable linger:
loginctl enable-linger "$USER"
# now user-instance units run from boot to shutdown regardless of
# logins. backups, agents, etc. work unattended.


# DROP-INS / systemctl edit — MODIFY UNITS THE RIGHT WAY

# DON'T edit /usr/lib/systemd/system/foo.service. it'll be overwritten
# on package upgrade. use a drop-in instead:
sudo systemctl edit sshd
# editor opens an empty file under /etc/systemd/system/sshd.service.d/
# called override.conf. anything you put there OVERLAYS the original.

# example: add MaxConnectionsPerSource to sshd:
#   [Service]
#   Environment=MAX_PER_SOURCE=10

# to edit the FULL unit (start with current contents instead of empty):
sudo systemctl edit --full sshd

# revert a drop-in:
sudo systemctl revert sshd


# TARGETS — WHAT BOOT IS REACHING

# the SysV "runlevels" replacement. fedora's default targets:
#
#   default.target          — symlink to one of:
#     multi-user.target     — text login, no GUI
#     graphical.target      — gdm + GUI session (workstation default)
#
# switch on the fly without rebooting:
sudo systemctl isolate multi-user.target     # drop to text mode (kills GUI)
sudo systemctl isolate graphical.target      # back to GUI

# permanent default:
sudo systemctl set-default multi-user.target
sudo systemctl get-default

# emergency / rescue (single-user, for repair):
#   add `systemd.unit=emergency.target` to kernel cmdline at GRUB.


# BOOT ANALYSIS

systemd-analyze                              # boot time summary
systemd-analyze blame                        # which units took longest
systemd-analyze critical-chain               # the boot critical path
systemd-analyze critical-chain sshd          # critical path for one unit
systemd-analyze plot > /tmp/boot.svg         # graphical boot timeline

# verify a unit file (catches typos before you reload):
systemd-analyze verify ~/.config/systemd/user/myapp.service


# RESOURCE LIMITS — CGROUPS WITHOUT FUSS

# every service runs in a cgroup. inspect:
systemctl status myapp                       # shows cgroup tree
systemd-cgls                                 # cgroup hierarchy
systemd-cgtop                                # top-like, by cgroup

# set limits on a running service (transient, until reload):
sudo systemctl set-property myapp MemoryMax=512M
sudo systemctl set-property myapp CPUQuota=200%       # 2 cores
sudo systemctl set-property myapp IOWeight=50

# persistent: add to a drop-in via `systemctl edit`.

# AD-HOC sandboxing — run a one-off command in its own cgroup:
systemd-run --user --pty --tty -p MemoryMax=256M htop
sudo systemd-run --unit=backup-now \
    -p MemoryMax=1G -p CPUQuota=50% \
    /usr/local/bin/my-backup-script


# QUICK REFERENCE — WHAT TO REACH FOR

#   "what's broken right now"          → systemctl --failed
#   "why did X fail"                   → journalctl -u X -n 100
#   "make this start at boot"          → systemctl enable --now X
#   "run my script weekly"             → write .service + .timer
#   "boot is slow"                     → systemd-analyze blame
#   "change a setting on a packaged service" → systemctl edit
#   "drop to text mode"                → systemctl isolate multi-user.target
#   "see what's hogging RAM/CPU"       → systemd-cgtop


GRUB — SHOWING THE MENU, MANAGING KERNELS
-----------------------------------------

# fedora ships GRUB2 with two layers of menu-hiding stacked on top of each
# other, which is why "I want to see the menu on boot" is a recurring
# fedora question. the layers:
#
#   1. /etc/default/grub        — GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE / GRUB_TIMEOUT
#   2. grubenv `menu_auto_hide` — fedora-specific "hide if last boot OK"
#
# you have to defeat BOTH to get a reliable menu on every boot.


# THE FIX (do all three for a permanent visible menu):

# 1. edit /etc/default/grub:
sudo vi /etc/default/grub
#    set or add:
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu          (default: "hidden" — this is the key flag)
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT=5                   (seconds; -1 = wait indefinitely for input)
#       GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU=true        (flatten "Advanced options" so EVERY
#                                         kernel shows at the top level instead
#                                         of being hidden in a submenu)
#       GRUB_DEFAULT=saved               (default is "saved" — remembers your
#                                         last selection. 0 = always first entry)

# 2. regenerate grub.cfg. on fedora 34+ the path is unified for BIOS + UEFI:
sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
#    older UEFI installs may still use:
#       sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/efi/EFI/fedora/grub.cfg
#    check which one exists on your system if the first command's output
#    looks too small.

# 3. disable fedora's auto-hide (the bit that hides the menu when the
#    PREVIOUS boot succeeded — independent of GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE):
sudo grub2-editenv - list                          # see current vars
sudo grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide          # show menu every boot
sudo grub2-editenv - unset boot_success            # clear the "last boot ok" flag
sudo grub2-editenv - unset boot_indeterminate      # clear "boot uncertain" flag

# verify after reboot. if the menu still hides, check `boot_success` keeps
# getting set — it's written by the user-systemd unit grub-boot-success.timer
# (~2.5 minutes after login). mask it if you want to be extra sure:
systemctl --user mask grub-boot-success.timer


# ONE-SHOT SHOW MENU AT BOOT (no config changes):
#   - UEFI: hold/tap Esc (or F8 on some firmware) at POST
#   - BIOS legacy: hold Shift
# Shift on UEFI usually does NOT work — common source of "I tried shift and
# nothing happened". use Esc on modern hardware.


# UNDERSTANDING THE MENU ENTRIES — BootLoaderSpec:

# since fedora 30, GRUB entries are NOT generated into grub.cfg the old
# way. instead each kernel is a separate .conf file in /boot/loader/entries/.
# the kernel package install drops a file there; GRUB discovers them at
# boot. NO grub2-mkconfig needed when a new kernel lands.
ls /boot/loader/entries/
cat /boot/loader/entries/*.conf | head -30

# the format (one entry per .conf):
#   title    Fedora Linux 44 (Workstation Edition) (6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64)
#   version  6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
#   linux    /vmlinuz-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
#   initrd   /initramfs-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64.img
#   options  root=UUID=... ro rhgb quiet ...
#   grub_users $grub_users
#   grub_arg --unrestricted
#   grub_class fedora


# `grubby` IS THE TOOL for managing these entries (don't hand-edit):

# list every installed kernel entry
sudo grubby --info=ALL

# show just the default
sudo grubby --default-kernel
sudo grubby --default-index
sudo grubby --default-title

# set a different default
sudo grubby --set-default=/boot/vmlinuz-6.11.4-200.fc44.x86_64
sudo grubby --set-default-index=2

# add a kernel command-line argument permanently (writes to every entry
# AND to /etc/kernel/cmdline so future kernels get it too)
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args='quiet splash'

# remove an argument
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --remove-args='quiet'

# remove a specific kernel entry (rare — usually let dnf handle it)
sudo grubby --remove-kernel=/boot/vmlinuz-6.10.3-200.fc44.x86_64


# KERNEL RETENTION — how many show up in the menu:

# fedora keeps the most recent 3 kernels by default. controlled by:
grep installonly_limit /etc/dnf/dnf.conf            # default: 3
#    bump it if you want more rollback options:
#       installonly_limit=5

# the rescue entry is generated once at install time as a special BLS
# entry — it's a kernel + initramfs frozen at install. don't expect it
# to track your current kernel. regenerate after a major upgrade:
sudo /etc/kernel/install.d/51-dracut-rescue.install add \
    $(uname -r) /boot $(uname -r)/initrd


# QUICK MENU INSPECTION:
sudo grub2-editenv - list                           # grubenv vars
sudo grubby --info=ALL | grep -E '^(index|title)='  # what the menu will show
ls /boot/loader/entries/                            # BLS entry files
cat /etc/default/grub                               # high-level config
cat /etc/kernel/cmdline                             # default cmdline for new kernels


# RECOMMENDED CONFIG for "show me everything, every boot":
#
#   /etc/default/grub:
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT_STYLE=menu
#       GRUB_TIMEOUT=5
#       GRUB_DISABLE_SUBMENU=true
#       GRUB_DEFAULT=saved
#
#   grubenv:
#       sudo grub2-editenv - unset menu_auto_hide
#
#   then:
#       sudo grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg
#       reboot


REPOS — OFFICIAL, RPM FUSION, COPR, FLATHUB
-------------------------------------------

# stock fedora repos cover free software only. enable these for the
# common "I want chrome / nvidia / mp3 codecs" needs:

# 1. RPM Fusion (free + nonfree codecs, multimedia, nvidia drivers):
sudo dnf install \
    https://mirrors.rpmfusion.org/free/fedora/rpmfusion-free-release-$(rpm -E %fedora).noarch.rpm \
    https://mirrors.rpmfusion.org/nonfree/fedora/rpmfusion-nonfree-release-$(rpm -E %fedora).noarch.rpm

# 2. flathub (cross-distro app sandboxing). fedora preconfigures a
#    filtered subset; add full flathub for everything:
flatpak remote-add --if-not-exists flathub \
    https://flathub.org/repo/flathub.flatpakrepo
flatpak remote-modify --enable flathub

# 3. COPR (community per-developer repos — same idea as the AUR, but with
#    binaries built on koji infrastructure):
sudo dnf copr enable user/project
sudo dnf install <pkg>

# multimedia codecs — the one-time setup most people want post-install:
sudo dnf swap ffmpeg-free ffmpeg --allowerasing
sudo dnf install gstreamer1-plugins-{bad-\*,good-\*,base} gstreamer1-plugin-openh264 \
    gstreamer1-plugins-bad-free-extras lame\* --exclude=gstreamer1-plugins-bad-free-devel


SELINUX — KEEP IT ENFORCING
---------------------------

# fedora's SELinux policy is mature. the right answer to AVC denials is
# almost never "permissive" or "disabled" — it's usually a missing label
# (`restorecon`) or a small policy adjustment (`audit2allow`).

# check status
sestatus
getenforce                                          # Enforcing / Permissive / Disabled

# investigate recent denials
sudo ausearch -m AVC -ts recent
sudo journalctl -b -t setroubleshoot

# auto-suggested fixes (read before applying)
sudo sealert -a /var/log/audit/audit.log

# common fix: relabel a file/dir to its policy-expected context
sudo restorecon -Rv /path/to/thing

# temporary permissive (next boot back to enforcing — useful for triage)
sudo setenforce 0

# DON'T disable in /etc/selinux/config unless you know exactly why.
# disabled SELinux means an unlabeled filesystem; turning it back on
# requires an autorelabel boot.


FIREWALLD — ZONE-BASED FIREWALL
-------------------------------

# fedora ships firewalld enabled with the FedoraWorkstation zone.
# day-to-day usage:

# show what's active
sudo firewall-cmd --get-active-zones
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all                        # default zone
sudo firewall-cmd --list-all --zone=public

# open a port — twice (--permanent for survival, no --permanent for live)
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp --permanent

# or in one command with auto-reload
sudo firewall-cmd --add-port=8080/tcp --permanent && sudo firewall-cmd --reload

# allow a service by name (curated list in /usr/lib/firewalld/services)
sudo firewall-cmd --add-service=http --permanent
sudo firewall-cmd --reload

# zone assignment for an interface (default: tied to NetworkManager profile)
sudo firewall-cmd --zone=trusted --change-interface=virbr0 --permanent


NETWORKING — NMCLI, DNS, VPNs, REMOTE ACCESS
--------------------------------------------

# the stack on fedora workstation:
#
#   NetworkManager   — the canonical network daemon. settings → wi-fi
#                      and settings → network drive it. nmcli is its CLI.
#   systemd-resolved — local DNS resolver. owns /etc/resolv.conf as a
#                      symlink. per-link DNS, DNS-over-TLS optional.
#   firewalld        — covered above. zones map to NM connections.
#   Avahi (mDNS)     — preinstalled, handles .local hostnames on LAN.
#
# the older `ifconfig` / `netstat` / `route` tools are NOT installed by
# default — they're considered legacy. use `ip`, `ss`, `nstat` from the
# iproute2 package (also preinstalled).


# NMCLI — THE EVERYDAY CLI

# overview
nmcli                                       # short summary
nmcli device status                         # interfaces + state
nmcli connection show                       # saved profiles
nmcli connection show --active              # currently in use

# wi-fi
nmcli device wifi list                      # scan
nmcli device wifi connect "SSID" password "pass"
nmcli device wifi connect "SSID" --ask      # prompt for password
nmcli connection up "SSID"                  # reconnect a saved profile
nmcli connection down "SSID"
nmcli radio wifi off                        # toggle wifi
nmcli radio wifi on

# ethernet
nmcli device connect enp3s0                 # bring up an interface
nmcli device disconnect enp3s0

# delete a saved profile
nmcli connection delete "old-network"

# show every detail about a connection
nmcli connection show "home-wifi"


# STATIC IP / DNS OVERRIDES (per connection)

# switch a profile to manual IPv4 with static address + DNS:
nmcli connection modify "home-wifi" \
    ipv4.method manual \
    ipv4.addresses 192.168.1.42/24 \
    ipv4.gateway 192.168.1.1 \
    ipv4.dns "1.1.1.1 9.9.9.9" \
    ipv4.dns-search "lan"

# revert to DHCP (the default):
nmcli connection modify "home-wifi" ipv4.method auto ipv4.addresses "" \
    ipv4.gateway "" ipv4.dns "" ipv4.dns-search ""

# changes apply on the next `nmcli connection up` of the profile.


# DNS — systemd-resolved

# /etc/resolv.conf is a SYMLINK to /run/systemd/resolve/stub-resolv.conf.
# editing it directly does nothing useful. all DNS config goes through
# NetworkManager (per-link) or systemd-resolved (global).

# inspect current state:
resolvectl status                           # per-link + global DNS
resolvectl statistics                       # cache hits, queries
resolvectl flush-caches                     # clear the DNS cache

# query (faster than dig + uses your actual resolver):
resolvectl query example.com
resolvectl query --type=MX example.com

# enable DNS-over-TLS globally:
sudo mkdir -p /etc/systemd/resolved.conf.d
sudo tee /etc/systemd/resolved.conf.d/dot.conf <<'EOF'
[Resolve]
DNS=1.1.1.1#cloudflare-dns.com 9.9.9.9#dns.quad9.net
DNSOverTLS=yes
DNSSEC=allow-downgrade
EOF
sudo systemctl restart systemd-resolved


# MDNS — .LOCAL HOSTNAMES ON THE LAN

# Avahi is preinstalled. find printers, NAS boxes, raspberry pis,
# anything advertising via mDNS:
avahi-browse -ar | head -50                 # all services
avahi-browse -ar | grep -i printer
ping fileserver.local                       # resolves via mDNS

# advertise this machine's services for others to find:
sudo dnf install nss-mdns                   # already on workstation
hostnamectl set-hostname mybox              # mybox.local will resolve


# SSH CLIENT — ~/.ssh/config IS THE TOOL

# the file most people don't realize they need. saves immense typing.
cat >>~/.ssh/config <<'EOF'
# global defaults
Host *
    ServerAliveInterval 60
    ServerAliveCountMax 3
    HashKnownHosts no
    ControlMaster auto
    ControlPath ~/.ssh/cm-%r@%h:%p
    ControlPersist 10m

# per-host shortcuts — `ssh prod` instead of full hostname
Host prod
    HostName prod.example.com
    User deploy
    Port 22
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_work

# jump host (ProxyJump) — multi-hop in one command
Host internal-db
    HostName 10.0.5.12
    User postgres
    ProxyJump prod
EOF
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/config

# ControlMaster + ControlPath multiplexing means subsequent connections
# to the same host reuse the existing TCP socket — instant. huge speed
# win for ansible / scp / repeated commands.

# ssh-agent is auto-started by GNOME (gnome-keyring). add keys:
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519                   # caches until logout
ssh-add -l                                  # currently cached
ssh-add -D                                  # forget all


# WIREGUARD — THE MODERN VPN PRIMITIVE

# kernel module is in fedora's kernel; tools are a one-line install.
sudo dnf install wireguard-tools

# NetworkManager has a built-in WireGuard backend. easiest path: get a
# .conf file from your VPN provider (or wireguard server) and import:
nmcli connection import type wireguard file ~/Downloads/wg0.conf
nmcli connection up wg0

# OR the wg-quick CLI path (no NetworkManager involvement):
sudo cp ~/Downloads/wg0.conf /etc/wireguard/
sudo wg-quick up wg0
sudo systemctl enable --now wg-quick@wg0     # autostart at boot

# inspect:
sudo wg show                                 # peers, handshake times
ip addr show wg0                             # local IP


# TAILSCALE — THE "JUST WORKS" VPN

# wireguard under the hood + a coordination server. zero NAT-traversal
# config, magic-DNS hostnames, exit nodes. fedora has it via COPR or
# the official repo:
sudo dnf config-manager addrepo --from-repofile=https://pkgs.tailscale.com/stable/fedora/tailscale.repo
sudo dnf install tailscale
sudo systemctl enable --now tailscaled
sudo tailscale up                            # browser-driven login

# day-to-day:
tailscale status                             # peer list + IPs
tailscale ip                                 # this machine's tailscale IP
ssh username@laptop                          # MagicDNS — no IP needed
tailscale ssh username@laptop                # built-in ssh with tailscale auth

# advanced:
sudo tailscale up --exit-node=other-machine  # route all traffic via peer
sudo tailscale up --advertise-exit-node      # offer this machine as an exit
sudo tailscale up --advertise-routes=192.168.1.0/24   # subnet router


# DIAGNOSTIC COMMANDS — THE MODERN STACK

# iproute2 (preinstalled) replaces ifconfig / netstat / route:
ip addr                                      # all interface addresses
ip -br addr                                  # brief, columnar
ip route                                     # routing table
ip -br link                                  # interface up/down state
ip neighbor                                  # ARP cache

# open ports / listening sockets (replaces netstat):
ss -tlnp                                     # TCP listening, with proc
ss -ulnp                                     # UDP listening
ss -tap                                      # all TCP, with proc
ss -s                                        # socket summary

# bandwidth / packet counters (replaces netstat -i):
nstat                                        # interface stats since boot
ip -s link                                   # per-interface counters

# connectivity / path:
ping -c 4 1.1.1.1
mtr 1.1.1.1                                  # interactive traceroute + ping
mtr -rwzc 10 example.com                     # report mode

# DNS troubleshooting:
resolvectl query example.com                 # uses your resolver
dig example.com                              # bypasses systemd-resolved
sudo dnf install bind-utils                  # if dig is missing

# capture packets (need sudo):
sudo dnf install wireshark-cli               # tshark + capture filters
sudo tshark -i wlan0 -f 'port 53'            # DNS traffic on wifi
sudo dnf install wireshark                   # the GUI


# FIREWALLD + NETWORKMANAGER ZONES

# every NM connection is assigned a firewalld zone. that's why your
# laptop's firewall is loose on home wifi (FedoraWorkstation zone) and
# stricter on public networks — the zone is per-profile.

# see current zone assignments:
sudo firewall-cmd --get-active-zones

# change a connection's zone (persists with the NM profile):
nmcli connection modify "coffee-shop-wifi" connection.zone public
nmcli connection up "coffee-shop-wifi"

# the FedoraWorkstation zone is intentionally permissive (libvirt,
# mdns, ssh, samba-client are all open by default). don't use it on
# untrusted networks.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. NETWORKMANAGER OVERRIDES YOUR /ETC/RESOLV.CONF EDITS. it's a
#    symlink; edits don't survive a reconnect. use per-connection
#    DNS via `nmcli connection modify` (above) or set DNS globally
#    in /etc/systemd/resolved.conf.d/.
#
# 2. VPN ROUTES ALL TRAFFIC WHEN YOU JUST WANTED LAN ACCESS. wg-quick
#    sets AllowedIPs=0.0.0.0/0 by default. for split-tunnel, edit
#    the .conf to list only your VPN subnet:
#       AllowedIPs = 10.0.0.0/8, 192.168.42.0/24
#
# 3. SSH FROZEN MID-SESSION. fix by setting ServerAliveInterval in
#    ~/.ssh/config (above) so the client probes periodically.
#
# 4. CAN'T REACH SAMBA / NFS SHARE. firewalld zone is too strict, OR
#    SELinux booleans aren't set. for samba client:
sudo setsebool -P use_samba_home_dirs on
#    for nfs:
sudo setsebool -P virt_use_nfs on
#
# 5. WIFI SLOW AFTER SUSPEND. NetworkManager + driver power-save
#    interaction. disable wifi power-save permanently:
sudo tee /etc/NetworkManager/conf.d/wifi-powersave.conf <<'EOF'
[connection]
wifi.powersave = 2
EOF
sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager
#    (powersave values: 0=use default, 2=disable, 3=enable)
#
# 6. TAILSCALE + SYSTEMD-RESOLVED ORDERING. on some installs the
#    tailscale interface comes up before systemd-resolved is ready
#    and DNS breaks until restart. fix:
sudo systemctl edit tailscaled
#    add:
#       [Unit]
#       After=systemd-resolved.service
#       Wants=systemd-resolved.service
#
# 7. mDNS / .local DOESN'T RESOLVE FROM A CONTAINER. expected —
#    rootless podman uses a different netns. on the host it works.


NVIDIA DRIVERS — RPM FUSION PATH
--------------------------------

# fedora ships nouveau (the open-source nvidia driver) out of the box.
# nouveau works for basic display but is significantly slower than the
# proprietary driver and lacks CUDA, NVENC, and full vulkan support.
# the supported path to the proprietary driver is RPM Fusion's
# akmod-nvidia (auto-rebuilds against new kernels via akmods.service,
# conceptually like DKMS but RPM-native).

# this is the kind of setup you do once per machine and want to get
# right the first time. the order below matters — installing akmod
# before the kernel headers update, or rebooting before the akmod
# build finishes, are the two ways people end up at a black screen.


# STEP 1 — IDENTIFY YOUR CARD

# the right driver variant depends on your GPU generation:
lspci | grep -iE 'vga|3d|2d'

#   - akmod-nvidia                — CURRENT branch (570.x). supports
#                                   Turing (GTX 16xx, RTX 20xx) and newer.
#                                   ALSO works for Maxwell + Pascal on
#                                   the open-kernel build but check
#                                   rpmfusion's nvidia page if unsure.
#   - akmod-nvidia-470xx          — LTS 470.x branch. Kepler (GTX 6xx /
#                                   7xx) and older Maxwell. for cards
#                                   the current driver dropped.
#   - akmod-nvidia-390xx          — legacy 390.x branch. Fermi era
#                                   (GeForce 4xx / 5xx). end-of-life
#                                   upstream; only install if you have
#                                   nothing else.
#
# unsure which to pick: check nvidia's "Supported Products" page or
# rpmfusion's "Howto/NVIDIA". if `nvidia-detect` is installed, it
# picks for you:
sudo dnf install nvidia-detect && nvidia-detect


# STEP 2 — PREREQUISITES (EVERYTHING IN SYNC)

# RPM Fusion must be enabled (see REPOS section above). then:

# fully update first — you want the kernel and kernel-headers in sync
# BEFORE akmod tries to build against them.
sudo dnf upgrade --refresh
sudo dnf install kernel-devel-$(uname -r) kernel-headers-$(uname -r)


# STEP 3 — INSTALL THE DRIVER

# CURRENT BRANCH (most people):
sudo dnf install akmod-nvidia xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda
#    xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda pulls in the CUDA RUNTIME libs (libcuda),
#    needed for hardware video decode (NVENC/NVDEC), pytorch GPU,
#    blender CUDA render, etc. install it unless you specifically don't
#    want CUDA on the box.

# steam / proton / wine — pull 32-bit libs:
sudo dnf install xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-libs.i686

# legacy 470xx branch (substitute the package names):
sudo dnf install akmod-nvidia-470xx xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-470xx-cuda


# STEP 4 — WAIT FOR THE AKMOD BUILD

# akmods.service builds the kmod in the background. 5-15 minutes on
# typical hardware. DO NOT REBOOT until it finishes — booting with the
# kmod half-built drops you on nouveau (or worse, a black screen on a
# system where nouveau is already blacklisted).

# watch the build:
sudo journalctl -fu akmods.service

# verify the module file exists for your running kernel:
ls /lib/modules/$(uname -r)/extra/nvidia/
modinfo -F version nvidia        # prints driver version once built

# if `modinfo` says nothing, the build hasn't finished or it failed.
# kick it manually:
sudo akmods --force


# STEP 5 — SECURE BOOT (skip if disabled in firmware)

# check your state:
mokutil --sb-state                 # SecureBoot enabled / disabled

# if enabled: akmod's built kmod is unsigned and shim will refuse to
# load it. RPM Fusion's akmod hooks generate a Machine Owner Key (MOK)
# pair at /var/lib/dkms/mok.{pub,priv} and sign the kmod with it. you
# enroll the pub side once:
sudo mokutil --import /var/lib/dkms/mok.pub
#    sets a one-time password. on next reboot, shim's MokManager menu
#    appears BEFORE GRUB — pick "Enroll MOK", confirm with that
#    password. enrollment is permanent until you remove it.

# verify enrollment after reboot:
mokutil --list-enrolled | grep -A2 "DKMS\|nvidia"

# easier path (if you don't care about secure boot): disable it in
# firmware. matters less on a desktop than a laptop you carry out.


# STEP 6 — WAYLAND / KMS MODESET

# nvidia-drm.modeset=1 enables proper KMS support, required for clean
# Wayland sessions, smooth tty switches, and gnome / kde wayland on
# nvidia. driver 545+ enables this by default, and rpmfusion configures
# it via /usr/lib/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf. verify:
cat /sys/module/nvidia_drm/parameters/modeset       # should be: Y

# if it's N, force it. either add the modprobe option:
sudo tee /etc/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf <<'EOF'
options nvidia-drm modeset=1
EOF
sudo dracut --force
#    or add it as a kernel cmdline arg:
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args='nvidia-drm.modeset=1'


# STEP 7 — REBOOT AND VERIFY

sudo reboot

# after login, confirm:
lsmod | grep -E 'nvidia|nouveau'    # nvidia loaded, nouveau ABSENT
nvidia-smi                           # GPU model + driver version + processes
glxinfo | grep -i 'opengl renderer'  # should say NVIDIA, not llvmpipe

# session type (wayland or x11):
echo $XDG_SESSION_TYPE


# HYBRID LAPTOP / OPTIMUS — RENDER OFFLOAD

# for laptops with both Intel/AMD iGPU + nvidia dGPU, the modern model
# is "on-demand": iGPU drives the display, nvidia handles render
# offload per-app. saves battery vs running everything on nvidia.

# verify both GPUs are present:
lspci -k | grep -EA3 'VGA|3D'

# launch a single app on nvidia from a terminal:
__NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia glxinfo \
    | grep 'OpenGL renderer'                # should now say NVIDIA

# convenient wrapper:
sudo tee /usr/local/bin/nv <<'EOF'
#!/bin/sh
exec env __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia \
         __VK_LAYER_NV_optimus=NVIDIA_only "$@"
EOF
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/nv
#    then: `nv blender`, `nv steam`, etc.

# steam per-game launch options for nvidia render offload:
#     __NV_PRIME_RENDER_OFFLOAD=1 __GLX_VENDOR_LIBRARY_NAME=nvidia %command%


# CUDA DEVELOPMENT (vs CUDA RUNTIME)

# xorg-x11-drv-nvidia-cuda installs runtime (libcuda) only — enough to
# RUN cuda apps (pytorch, blender, ffmpeg-nvenc). for compiling cuda
# code you need the toolkit. two paths:
#
# a) nvidia's official cuda repo (most cuda versions, large download)
sudo dnf config-manager addrepo --from-repofile=https://developer.download.nvidia.com/compute/cuda/repos/fedora41/x86_64/cuda-fedora41.repo
sudo dnf install cuda-toolkit
#    fedora 44 isn't always in nvidia's repo on day one — substitute
#    fedora41 or fedora42 as a placeholder; the binaries are usually
#    forward-compatible. check developer.nvidia.com for current list.
#
# b) python-only path: install pytorch / tensorflow wheels that bundle
#    their own cuda libs. no system toolkit needed.


# COMMON FAILURES AND FIXES

# 1. "nvidia kernel module missing" / black screen after reboot.
#    you rebooted before akmod finished. boot to multi-user mode
#    (add `3` to kernel cmdline at the GRUB menu — that's why we
#    showed the GRUB menu earlier), log in, then:
sudo akmods --force
sudo systemctl isolate graphical.target
#
# 2. nouveau still loaded alongside nvidia. check the blacklist:
cat /usr/lib/modprobe.d/nvidia.conf
#    rpmfusion should drop a blacklist entry. if not:
sudo tee /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist-nouveau.conf <<'EOF'
blacklist nouveau
options nouveau modeset=0
EOF
sudo dracut --force
#
# 3. kernel update broke nvidia. akmod usually rebuilds on `dnf
#    upgrade`, but if it didn't fire:
sudo akmods --force --kernels $(uname -r)
sudo dracut --force
#
# 4. wayland tearing / glitching. driver 545+ should be fine. if
#    not, log out and pick "GNOME on Xorg" at the gdm session
#    picker — GNOME 47+ still ships the xorg session as an optional
#    package:
sudo dnf install gnome-session-xsession
#    KDE Plasma's wayland on nvidia is generally smoother than
#    GNOME's as of 2026.
#
# 5. screen tearing in X11. enable the nvidia force-composition
#    pipeline in xorg conf, or use a compositor (picom).
#
# 6. external monitor not detected after suspend. driver power
#    management quirk. on most setups this is fixed by:
sudo systemctl enable --now nvidia-suspend.service \
    nvidia-resume.service nvidia-hibernate.service


# REMOVAL / ROLLBACK TO NOUVEAU

sudo dnf remove '*nvidia*' --noautoremove
sudo dnf install xorg-x11-drv-nouveau          # if dnf removed it
sudo rm /etc/modprobe.d/blacklist-nouveau.conf 2>/dev/null
sudo rm /etc/modprobe.d/nvidia-modeset.conf 2>/dev/null
sudo dracut --force
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL --remove-args='nvidia-drm.modeset=1'
sudo reboot


SECURE BOOT — NOTES
-------------------

# fedora's shim is signed by Microsoft, so secure boot works out of the
# box for the default kernel and the shipped grub. third-party kmods
# (nvidia, virtualbox, dkms-built modules) need signing. options:
#   - disable secure boot in firmware (simplest, least secure)
#   - enroll a MOK and sign kmods (correct path; see above)
#   - use sbctl to manage your own keys (advanced)

# verify state:
mokutil --sb-state                                  # SecureBoot enabled / disabled
mokutil --list-enrolled


HARDWARE / FIRMWARE — fwupd
---------------------------

# LVFS (the linux vendor firmware service) is wired up out of the box.
# check / apply firmware updates from userspace, no reboot to firmware
# update utility:
fwupdmgr get-devices                                # what's reported
fwupdmgr refresh                                    # pull metadata
fwupdmgr get-updates                                # what's available
sudo fwupdmgr update                                # apply (reboots into UEFI for some)


