FINGERPRINT READER (LAPTOPS)
----------------------------

# fedora's stack: libfprint (driver library) + fprintd (daemon) +
# authselect (PAM wiring). the biggest gotcha is hardware support —
# many recent laptops ship Goodix or Synaptics readers that need
# specific libfprint versions or third-party drivers. always verify
# support FIRST before installing anything.


# STEP 1 — identify the reader and check support
lsusb | grep -iE 'fingerprint|sensor|biometric'
# cross-reference vendor/product IDs at:
#   https://fprint.freedesktop.org/supported-devices.html


# STEP 2 — install fprintd (usually already on Workstation)
sudo dnf install fprintd fprintd-pam


# STEP 3 — enroll a finger
fprintd-enroll                                # default: right-index
fprintd-enroll -f left-index                  # specific finger
fprintd-list "$USER"                          # verify enrolled fingers
fprintd-delete "$USER" -f left-index          # remove one
# GUI path: Settings → Users → Fingerprint Login (toggle only
# appears when a supported reader is detected).


# STEP 4 — wire into PAM via authselect
# DON'T hand-edit /etc/pam.d/* on fedora — authselect manages PAM
# via profiles, and direct edits get overwritten.
sudo authselect enable-feature with-fingerprint
sudo authselect apply-changes
authselect current                            # verify the feature is on
# this adds fingerprint to sudo, su, login, GDM, and polkit. password
# remains the fallback if the reader fails or you cancel the prompt.


# STEP 5 — test
sudo -k && sudo true                          # should prompt for fingerprint
# then lock the screen (Super+L) and try GDM unlock.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. lsusb shows the reader but `fprintd-enroll` says "no devices".
#    libfprint doesn't support that exact revision yet. options:
#      - check upstream libfprint issue tracker for your USB ID
#      - try a newer libfprint from COPR if available
#      - for some Synaptics readers, the out-of-tree open-fprintd +
#        python-validity drivers exist (RPM build required; messy)
#
# 2. resume from suspend kills the reader. quick fix:
sudo systemctl restart fprintd
#    if it's persistent, file the kernel bug — there are open ones
#    for several laptop models, sometimes fixed by a firmware update
#    (worth running `fwupdmgr update` first).
#
# 3. Goodix 53xx family is hit-or-miss. some IDs (53b2, 5395, etc.)
#    are in mainline libfprint; others still need vendor patches.
#    check your specific ID against the supported-devices list, not
#    just "Goodix Generic".
#
# 4. fingerprint does NOT unlock LUKS. fingerprint kicks in only
#    post-boot (GDM, sudo, polkit). pre-boot biometric unlock isn't
#    a thing on linux. for hands-off boot, use TPM-backed unlock via
#    systemd-cryptenroll (see [[luks]] / the fedora-to-endeavouros
#    LUKS section) — different mechanism, different threat model.
#
# 5. multiple users: each user enrolls their own fingerprints. there's
#    no system-wide enrollment. enroll while logged in as the user.
#
# 6. disable / uninstall the wiring cleanly:
sudo authselect disable-feature with-fingerprint
sudo authselect apply-changes
fprintd-delete "$USER"                        # remove enrolled prints
sudo dnf remove fprintd-pam                   # optional


POWER MANAGEMENT — SLEEP, HIBERNATE, PROFILES
---------------------------------------------

# the stack on fedora workstation:
#
#   power-profiles-daemon (PPD)  — performance / balanced / power-saver
#                                  modes. fedora's default since F35,
#                                  replaced TLP for most users.
#   GNOME Settings → Power        — UI on top of gsettings keys
#   systemd-logind                — lid switch, power button, idle
#   upower                        — battery state introspection
#   the kernel's cpufreq governor — intel_pstate / amd-pstate driver +
#                                  schedutil governor by default
#
# the four sleep modes (`cat /sys/power/state` shows what's supported):
#
#   suspend (s2idle / S3) — to RAM, quick resume, small power draw
#   hibernate             — to disk, zero power, slow resume
#   suspend-then-hibernate — to RAM first, then to disk after a delay
#   hybrid-sleep          — to RAM + disk simultaneously


# AUTOMATIC SUSPEND TIMEOUTS

# Settings → Power → "Automatic Suspend" (it's a click-through, not an
# inline toggle — opens a dialog with separate "On Battery" and
# "Plugged In" toggles).
#
# desktops or docked-only laptops: no battery = GNOME hides the
# battery/AC distinction. you get a single "Suspend when inactive"
# toggle, or nothing.

# CLI equivalents under org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power:
gsettings list-recursively org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power \
    | grep -E 'sleep|idle'

# AC behavior (plugged in):
gsettings set org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power \
    sleep-inactive-ac-type 'suspend'        # or 'nothing' / 'hibernate'
gsettings set org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power \
    sleep-inactive-ac-timeout 1800          # 30 min

# battery behavior:
gsettings set org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power \
    sleep-inactive-battery-type 'suspend'
gsettings set org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power \
    sleep-inactive-battery-timeout 900      # 15 min

# screen blank — separate setting; screen off but system stays awake:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.session idle-delay 600

# workstation defaults: screen blanks at 5 min, battery suspends at 15
# min, AC suspends at 20 min. it's never literally "always on" by
# default, but people often miss the AC case because the timeout is
# generous.


# POWER PROFILES

# performance / balanced / power-saver via power-profiles-daemon.
# CLI:
powerprofilesctl list
powerprofilesctl get
powerprofilesctl set performance              # max perf, hot, loud fans
powerprofilesctl set balanced                 # default
powerprofilesctl set power-saver              # tighten timeouts, cap CPU
powerprofilesctl version

# GUI: Settings → Power → Power Mode, OR click the system-tray battery
# icon — the three options appear there.
#
# the kernel responsively biases the cpufreq governor and may
# tweak boost / thermal headroom based on the chosen profile.


# LID SWITCH AND POWER BUTTON — logind, not GNOME

# /etc/systemd/logind.conf controls these, NOT the GNOME panel:
#
#   HandleLidSwitch=                  what closing the lid does
#   HandleLidSwitchExternalPower=     same, but only when plugged in
#   HandleLidSwitchDocked=            same, but only when docked
#   HandlePowerKey=                   short power-button press
#   HandlePowerKeyLongPress=          held power-button press
#   HandleSuspendKey=                 hardware suspend key
#   HandleHibernateKey=               hardware hibernate key
#
# valid actions: ignore, poweroff, reboot, halt, kexec, suspend,
# hibernate, hybrid-sleep, suspend-then-hibernate, lock.

# common scenario: laptop hooked to an external monitor, don't want
# lid-close to suspend:
sudo mkdir -p /etc/systemd/logind.conf.d
sudo tee /etc/systemd/logind.conf.d/lid.conf <<'EOF'
[Login]
HandleLidSwitch=suspend
HandleLidSwitchExternalPower=ignore
HandleLidSwitchDocked=ignore
EOF
sudo systemctl restart systemd-logind
# warning: this kicks you out of your gnome session. save first.


# HIBERNATE — SETUP IS NOT AUTOMATIC

# hibernate writes the entire RAM state to swap, then powers off
# fully. it requires:
#   - swap space >= total RAM size (ideally with ~20% headroom)
#   - a `resume=` kernel parameter pointing at the swap location
#   - the kernel built with hibernation support (fedora's is)
#   - secure boot may need extra config (signed hibernation image)

# check if hibernation is currently available:
cat /sys/power/state                          # should list 'disk'
cat /sys/power/disk                           # methods available
systemctl status hibernate.target

# if you picked "Swap (with Hibernate)" in calamares / anaconda at
# install time, this is already set up:
swapon --show                                 # confirm swap >= RAM
cat /proc/cmdline | grep -o 'resume=[^ ]*'    # confirm resume= present

# if NOT — easiest fix is creating a swapfile (btrfs needs care):
sudo touch /swapfile
sudo chattr +C /swapfile                      # btrfs: nodatacow REQUIRED
sudo fallocate -l 32G /swapfile                # match your RAM
sudo chmod 600 /swapfile
sudo mkswap /swapfile
sudo swapon /swapfile
echo '/swapfile none swap defaults 0 0' | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
# add resume= kernel arg pointing at swap device + offset:
sudo grubby --update-kernel=ALL \
    --args="resume=UUID=$(findmnt / -no UUID) resume_offset=$(sudo filefrag -v /swapfile | awk 'NR==4 {print $4}' | tr -d '.')"

# test:
systemctl hibernate
# after resume, verify: `last -x | head` should show no clean shutdown
# between hibernation and now.


# SUSPEND-THEN-HIBERNATE — the hybrid people actually want

# suspends to RAM first (quick resume), then hibernates after a
# configurable delay (saves battery overnight). configure in
# /etc/systemd/sleep.conf:
sudo tee /etc/systemd/sleep.conf.d/hybrid.conf <<'EOF'
[Sleep]
HibernateDelaySec=2h
EOF
# trigger:
systemctl suspend-then-hibernate
# bind it to lid-close (laptops):
#   set HandleLidSwitch=suspend-then-hibernate in logind.conf
# bind it to the gnome auto-suspend action:
#   gsettings set org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power \
#       sleep-inactive-battery-type 'suspend-then-hibernate'


# TLP vs POWER-PROFILES-DAEMON — DON'T RUN BOTH

# historical advice ("install TLP for laptop battery") is outdated for
# fedora. power-profiles-daemon is the default and is what GNOME's
# power-mode selector controls. TLP is a separate tool with much
# finer-grained tuning knobs (per-device USB autosuspend, PCIe ASPM,
# wifi power-save, disk APM, etc.).
#
# they CONFLICT. running both produces unpredictable behavior. if you
# install TLP, you must mask PPD:
sudo dnf install tlp tlp-rdw
sudo systemctl mask power-profiles-daemon
sudo systemctl enable --now tlp
# config: /etc/tlp.conf

# the question of which to use: PPD is enough for 90% of users. TLP
# is worth it ONLY if you've measured a real problem PPD can't fix
# (specific USB device draining battery at idle, wifi card not
# entering low-power state, etc.). default to PPD.


# BATTERY MONITORING

# list power devices:
upower -e

# detailed battery state (substitute the BAT path from -e):
upower -i $(upower -e | grep -m1 BAT)
# look for: energy-full / energy-full-design (capacity vs new)
#           capacity (% of design — battery health, <80% means worn)
#           time-to-empty (current rate of discharge)

# gnome-power-statistics shows it graphically:
sudo dnf install gnome-power-manager
gnome-power-statistics


# POWERTOP — IDENTIFY POWER HOGS

sudo dnf install powertop
sudo powertop                                  # interactive UI
sudo powertop --html=/tmp/power-report.html    # report

# `sudo powertop --auto-tune` applies every suggested tweak in one
# shot. famously aggressive — can break wifi, USB devices, brightness
# keys. don't run it blindly. read the suggestions, apply the safe
# ones in /etc/tmpfiles.d/.


# COMMON GOTCHAS

# 1. SUSPEND WAKES UP IMMEDIATELY. usually a USB device generating wake
#    events (mouse jitter, keyboard, hub). find culprits:
cat /proc/acpi/wakeup
#    disable wake from a device (substitute the device id):
echo XHC | sudo tee /proc/acpi/wakeup

# 2. WIFI / BLUETOOTH BROKEN AFTER SUSPEND. firmware quirk on some
#    chipsets. quick fix:
sudo systemctl restart NetworkManager
#    persistent: kernel cmdline workaround `iwlwifi.power_save=0`
#    or similar (varies by chipset).

# 3. NVIDIA + SUSPEND. covered in the NVIDIA section above —
#    enable the nvidia-suspend / -resume / -hibernate systemd units.

# 4. HIBERNATE FAILS SILENTLY. usually swap is too small, OR resume=
#    kernel parameter is missing or wrong:
journalctl -b -1 -g hibernate                  # check the failed boot
journalctl -b 0 -g resume

# 5. SECURE BOOT + HIBERNATE. some firmwares refuse to resume a
#    hibernation image under secure boot (treats it as code-signing
#    violation). either disable secure boot or use a signed
#    kernel + signed hibernation setup (rare on fedora workstation).

# 6. BATTERY % JUMPS OR STICKS AT 0% / 100%. calibration drift in
#    the embedded controller. discharge to empty + charge to full a
#    few cycles, or check vendor's firmware via fwupd for a calibration
#    update.

# 7. DISABLE SLEEP ENTIRELY (servers, kiosks). mask the targets:
sudo systemctl mask sleep.target suspend.target hibernate.target \
    hybrid-sleep.target

# 8. DESKTOPS SOMETIMES SUSPEND ON SCREEN BLANK. usually because GNOME
#    detected a fake "battery" device (UPS plugged in to USB) and is
#    applying laptop defaults. either remove the udev quirk or set
#    sleep-inactive-ac-type='nothing'.


# WHAT TO CHECK FIRST WHEN POWER MISBEHAVES

powerprofilesctl get                           # current profile
gsettings list-recursively org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.power \
    | grep -E 'sleep|idle'
cat /etc/systemd/logind.conf                   # lid / power button
journalctl -b -g -E 'suspend|hibernate|resume' # recent transitions
upower -i $(upower -e | grep -m1 BAT)          # battery state


GNOME TIPS (Workstation default)
--------------------------------

# fedora ships GNOME on Wayland by default. xorg session is removable
# but still available — install gnome-session-xsession to add it back
# to gdm's session picker. KDE Plasma is its own Edition (and Spin);
# this section is GNOME-specific.


# MIDDLE-CLICK PASTE — the X11 PRIMARY workflow on GNOME

# how it works (built into GTK, no install / toggle needed):
#   - SELECTING text auto-copies to the PRIMARY selection. instant. no
#     Ctrl+C.
#   - MIDDLE-CLICK pastes from PRIMARY.
#   - Ctrl+C / Ctrl+V use a SEPARATE buffer (CLIPBOARD). the two
#     buffers don't overlap — selecting doesn't stomp your Ctrl+C
#     contents.
# this works on both Wayland and X11 in GNOME for native GTK apps.

# touchpad users — no physical middle button. two-finger tap maps to
# middle click via:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.touchpad middle-click-emulation true

# firefox: check `about:config` → `middlemouse.paste` is true. it is
# by default on Linux builds; only a problem if you've imported a
# Windows profile.

# wayland-native apps that don't participate: a few Electron apps
# still miss primary-selection support. GTK / Qt / chromium all
# work. if a specific app misbehaves, that's a per-app bug, not a
# GNOME setting.

# vs code: enable selection-clipboard paste explicitly (it's on by
# default on Linux, but worth knowing):
#   "editor.selectionClipboard": true


# PTYXIS — the new default terminal (Fedora 41+)

# fedora replaced gnome-terminal with Ptyxis as the default terminal in
# Workstation 41. Ptyxis is GTK4 + container-aware (transparent toolbox /
# distrobox / podman integration) and uses VTE under the hood — same
# terminal widget gnome-terminal used. middle-click paste works by
# default for the same reason gnome-terminal's did.
#
# IMPORTANT: Ptyxis has its OWN Preferences dialog (hamburger menu →
# Preferences, or Ctrl+,). it looks visually identical to gnome-tweaks
# and other GTK4 settings panels — easy to confuse the two. terminal-
# specific settings (palette, font, scrollback, paste behavior,
# bell, container defaults, profile management) live there, not in
# tweaks.
#
# inspect Ptyxis's settings from the CLI:
gsettings list-recursively org.gnome.Ptyxis | grep -iE 'paste|scroll|bell'
#
# if middle-click paste DOESN'T work in Ptyxis (rare), the likely
# culprits — in order of frequency:
#   1. touchpad with no physical middle button → enable middle-click
#      emulation (gsetting above).
#   2. a tiling extension (Forge, Pop Shell) grabbing middle-click for
#      window management.
#   3. profile setting disabled — Preferences → Profiles → <name> →
#      look for paste / clipboard options.
#
# container integration is the new selling point: Ptyxis detects
# toolbox / distrobox / podman containers and offers them in the
# "New Tab" dropdown. no manual `toolbox enter` typing.
ptyxis --tab --container=<name>             # open a tab in a container
ptyxis --working-directory=/path            # open with a starting cwd

# if you preferred gnome-terminal and want it back:
sudo dnf install gnome-terminal
xdg-mime default org.gnome.Terminal.desktop x-scheme-handler/terminal
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.default-applications.terminal exec gnome-terminal


# GHOSTTY — Mitchell Hashimoto's GPU-rendered terminal

# ghostty (1.0 released Dec 2024) is a Zig-built GPU-rendered terminal,
# native macOS app + GTK4 on Linux. it's in the same lane as alacritty /
# kitty / wezterm: performance-focused, less DE-integrated, cross-
# platform. NOT in Fedora's official repos. three install paths, in
# increasing friction order:

# 1. COPR (most common Fedora path — the closest analog to AUR or
#    ubuntu's snap for ghostty). updates flow via `dnf upgrade`:
sudo dnf copr enable pgdev/ghostty
sudo dnf install ghostty

# 2. flatpak from flathub. sandboxed; expect the usual flatpak caveats
#    (home-dir access via Flatseal, slightly slower first launch, some
#    $TERM / terminfo quirks at the sandbox boundary):
flatpak install flathub com.mitchellh.ghostty

# 3. build from source. you pay maintenance cost but get HEAD or any
#    pinned tag:
sudo dnf install zig gtk4-devel libadwaita-devel
git clone https://github.com/ghostty-org/ghostty.git
cd ghostty && zig build -Doptimize=ReleaseFast
sudo zig build install -Doptimize=ReleaseFast --prefix /usr/local

# canonical install instructions move over time. before relying on the
# COPR or flatpak ID above, sanity-check ghostty.org/download — it's
# the source of truth for current packaging.

# config lives at ~/.config/ghostty/config (single file, plain key=value).
# the doc page lists every option: ghostty.org/docs/config

# ghostty vs ptyxis: not an either/or. ghostty as a daily driver +
# ptyxis when you want quick toolbox/distrobox tabs is a common setup.
# set the default with:
xdg-mime default com.mitchellh.ghostty.desktop x-scheme-handler/terminal
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.default-applications.terminal exec ghostty


# THE TWEAK STACK — what to install on day one

sudo dnf install gnome-tweaks gnome-extensions-app dconf-editor

# - gnome-tweaks         — top-level toggles GNOME upstream removed from
#                          Settings (fonts, window controls, startup apps,
#                          legacy extensions list, mouse acceleration).
# - gnome-extensions-app — manage installed extensions (enable/disable,
#                          configure, remove). counterpart to the
#                          extensions.gnome.org browser flow.
# - dconf-editor         — the regedit-equivalent for GNOME's settings DB.
#                          last resort when neither Settings nor Tweaks
#                          exposes the knob you need.

# fedora removes a few GNOME defaults you might want back:
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-appindicator           # system tray icons
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-caffeine              # inhibit suspend
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-pop-shell             # tiling WM mode
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-dash-to-dock          # macos-style dock
sudo dnf install gnome-shell-extension-just-perfection       # granular UI tuning


# EXTENSIONS — browser install vs dnf install

# two paths to install GNOME extensions:
#   1. dnf — packaged extensions, survive GNOME version bumps better,
#            update with the rest of the system. preferred where available.
#   2. extensions.gnome.org — browser-driven install. needs the
#            "GNOME Shell integration" browser extension AND the
#            gnome-browser-connector host (`sudo dnf install
#            gnome-browser-connector`). easier for things not in the
#            fedora repos.

# critical default-extensions-on-fedora to know about:
#   - background-logo-extension  — adds the fedora "f" watermark to the
#                                  desktop wallpaper. cosmetic. disable
#                                  via gnome-extensions-app if it bugs you.
#   - window-list                 — bottom taskbar; comes with the
#                                   "Classic" session, not standard.

# extensions DO break across major GNOME versions. fedora 44 ships
# GNOME 47; a fedora upgrade jumps GNOME too. check the extension's
# supported versions before a release upgrade — or just disable
# them all first and re-enable after.


# COMMON gsettings / dconf KNOBS

# show minimize + maximize window buttons (removed from GNOME default).
# this is the most-asked "where did my buttons go" GNOME question.
#
#   gnome-tweaks path: Tweaks → Windows → Titlebar Buttons → toggle
#                      Maximize and Minimize on. takes effect instantly,
#                      no logout needed.
#   gsettings path (same thing, scriptable):
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.wm.preferences button-layout 'appmenu:minimize,maximize,close'
#
# the prefix before the colon = LEFT side; after = RIGHT side. swap
# for macos-style controls on the left:
#       'close,minimize,maximize:appmenu'
#
# CSD vs SSD caveat: most modern GNOME apps (Files, Settings, Text
# Editor, gedit, etc.) use Client-Side Decorations — they don't have
# a traditional titlebar, they put window controls inside the header
# bar. the button-layout setting controls that header bar too, so
# you'll get min/max buttons there. older GTK3 apps / Qt apps /
# Electron apps with Server-Side Decorations show the buttons in a
# traditional titlebar.

# disable mouse acceleration (gamers / pixel-art):
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.mouse accel-profile 'flat'

# disable natural ("reverse") scrolling on a normal mouse:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.mouse natural-scroll false

# tap-to-click on touchpad:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.peripherals.touchpad tap-to-click true

# fixed (not dynamic) workspace count:
gsettings set org.gnome.mutter dynamic-workspaces false
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.wm.preferences num-workspaces 4

# show seconds in the top-bar clock:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface clock-show-seconds true

# show battery percentage on laptops:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface show-battery-percentage true

# 12 vs 24 hour clock:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface clock-format '24h'

# disable animations entirely (perceived snappier, slightly less polish):
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface enable-animations false

# dark mode:
gsettings set org.gnome.desktop.interface color-scheme 'prefer-dark'

# every gsettings command above has a Tweaks or Settings UI equivalent.
# use the CLI when you want reproducibility (a setup script you can
# rerun on a fresh install).


# FRACTIONAL SCALING (4K / hi-DPI displays)

# wayland fractional scaling is now stable in GNOME 47+. enable with:
gsettings set org.gnome.mutter experimental-features "['scale-monitor-framebuffer']"
# then Settings → Displays exposes 125% / 150% / 175% options.
# XWayland apps will look slightly softer (they render at integer scale
# and get downsampled); native wayland apps are crisp.


# WAYLAND vs XORG SESSION AT LOGIN

# fedora 44 defaults to wayland. you can pick "GNOME on Xorg" at the
# gear icon on the gdm login screen IF gnome-session-xsession is
# installed:
sudo dnf install gnome-session-xsession

# check current session type:
echo $XDG_SESSION_TYPE                  # "wayland" or "x11"
loginctl show-session $XDG_SESSION_ID -p Type


# GNOME SOFTWARE vs DNF

# GNOME Software (the app store GUI) backends:
#   - rpm packages from fedora repos (dnf under the hood)
#   - flatpak from flathub / fedora-flatpaks
#   - fwupd firmware updates
# for power users: stick to `dnf` for system packages, GNOME Software
# for flatpak apps and firmware. GNOME Software's rpm view sometimes
# hides packages that have no .desktop file or no metainfo XML.


# TOUCHPAD / GESTURES

# three-finger swipe for workspace switching is built in on Wayland —
# no extension needed. Settings → Touchpad shows the gesture options.
# on X11 you need `touchegg` to get the same gestures.

sudo dnf install xdotool ydotool        # if you want to script input
sudo dnf install gestures-shell-extension     # if you want extra mappings


# KEYBOARD SHORTCUTS

# Settings → Keyboard → View and Customize Shortcuts is the GUI. for
# scripting, the path is org.gnome.desktop.wm.keybindings + custom
# entries under org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys.

# add a custom Ctrl+Alt+T → launch gnome-terminal binding:
cat >/tmp/term-keybind.sh <<'EOF'
schema=org.gnome.settings-daemon.plugins.media-keys
custom=custom-keybindings
path=/org/gnome/settings-daemon/plugins/media-keys/custom-keybindings/custom0/

gsettings set $schema $custom "[\"$path\"]"
gsettings set $schema.custom-keybinding:$path name 'terminal'
gsettings set $schema.custom-keybinding:$path command 'gnome-terminal'
gsettings set $schema.custom-keybinding:$path binding '<Control><Alt>t'
EOF
bash /tmp/term-keybind.sh

# (Ctrl+Alt+T is not bound by default in GNOME — long-time linux users
#  often want it back. fun fact: there's no terminal hotkey at all
#  out of the box.)


# RESET TO DEFAULTS

# revert a single setting:
gsettings reset org.gnome.desktop.interface color-scheme

# nuke the entire GNOME config back to defaults (RUNS IN YOUR SESSION,
# logs you out cleanly):
dconf reset -f /org/gnome/


CLAUDE CODE — INSTALL ON FEDORA
-------------------------------

# anthropic's CLI agent. not in fedora repos. three install paths,
# ordered by simplicity. see also [[claude-code]] for the ptyxis
# shift+enter workaround.


# 1. NATIVE INSTALLER (recommended)
# self-contained binary. no Node.js dep, no system-wide JS toolchain.
# canonical URL is on claude.com/claude-code — check there if the
# script URL below has rotated:
curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash
which claude && claude --version
#
# lands in ~/.local/bin (already on fedora's user PATH). no sudo.
# updates: `claude update` or just re-run the installer.
# uninstall: rm -rf ~/.local/share/claude ~/.local/bin/claude


# 2. NPM (traditional path)
# works fine but you're now maintaining a global Node install just
# for one CLI. preferred only if you already use npm for other tools.
sudo dnf install nodejs npm
npm install -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code
#
# avoid sudo for global installs by setting a per-user prefix:
mkdir -p ~/.npm-global
npm config set prefix ~/.npm-global
echo 'export PATH=~/.npm-global/bin:$PATH' >> ~/.zshrc
exec zsh
#
# update: `npm update -g @anthropic-ai/claude-code`


# 3. HOMEBREW ON LINUX (only if already using brew)
brew install anthropic/claude/claude-code


# AUTH — two modes

# subscription (Pro / Max) — usual choice for individual use:
claude login

# API key — billable per token; right choice for CI / scripted use:
export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
# put it in ~/.zshrc or a per-project .envrc (direnv) rather than
# typing it interactively.


# PTYXIS NOTE
# claude code's shift+enter (insert newline mid-prompt) does NOT work
# in ptyxis out of the box — ptyxis sends the same byte sequence as
# plain enter. workarounds (covered in [[claude-code]]):
#   - run `/terminal-setup` inside claude code (works for kitty, iterm2,
#     vs code; ptyxis support is partial)
#   - use Ctrl+J to insert a newline
#   - end the line with a backslash before pressing enter
# the cleanest fix is to use a different terminal — see GHOSTTY above
# (its keybinding for shift+enter is configurable and works cleanly).


VIRTUAL MACHINES
----------------

# fedora has good libvirt + KVM + QEMU support out of the box. the
# "which tool" question depends on how much control you want:
#
#   gnome-boxes           — easiest. fewest clicks, OS catalog, minimal
#                           config. great for "try this ISO for an
#                           afternoon". no snapshots / custom networks /
#                           passthrough in the GUI.
#   virt-manager          — full libvirt GUI. snapshots, custom networks,
#                           USB / PCI passthrough, NUMA, complex storage.
#                           the power-user default.
#   cockpit + cockpit-machines — web UI at https://localhost:9090. best
#                           for headless hosts or browser-driven mgmt.
#   virsh / virt-install  — canonical CLI. scriptable, reproducible. the
#                           right answer for "define this VM in a file
#                           i can commit to git".
#   vagrant + vagrant-libvirt — declarative Vagrantfile, `vagrant up`.
#                           great for reproducible dev environments.
#                           see [[vagrant]].
#   distrobox / toolbox   — NOT VMs. containers that look like a full
#                           alternate linux userspace. share your /home,
#                           GPU, network. usually the right answer when
#                           the real question is "i want a different
#                           distro environment for a task", not "i need
#                           full isolation".


# RECOMMENDED INSTALL — both GUIs share the libvirt backend, VMs
# created in one show up in the other:
sudo dnf install gnome-boxes virt-manager libvirt qemu-kvm virt-viewer \
    libguestfs-tools libosinfo

# permissions: enable libvirtd, add yourself to the libvirt group so
# you don't need sudo for per-user operations:
sudo systemctl enable --now libvirtd
sudo usermod -aG libvirt "$USER"
# log out and back in (or `newgrp libvirt`) for the group to take effect.


# KVM HARDWARE CHECK — confirm hardware virt is on
lscpu | grep -E 'Virtualization|vmx|svm'      # vmx = intel, svm = amd
ls -l /dev/kvm                                # should exist + be readable
                                              # by your user (via the kvm group)

# if /dev/kvm is missing, virt is disabled in firmware (Intel VT-x /
# AMD-V). enable it in BIOS/UEFI and reboot.

# nested virt (run VMs inside VMs — useful for testing virt-stacks):
cat /sys/module/kvm_intel/parameters/nested   # should be Y
# enable persistently if N:
echo 'options kvm_intel nested=1' | sudo tee /etc/modprobe.d/kvm.conf
sudo modprobe -r kvm_intel && sudo modprobe kvm_intel


# virsh — DAILY COMMANDS

virsh list --all                              # every VM, running or off
virsh start fedora-test
virsh shutdown fedora-test                    # graceful (ACPI)
virsh destroy fedora-test                     # power off (force, no save)
virsh reboot fedora-test
virsh suspend fedora-test                     # pause to RAM
virsh resume fedora-test
virsh console fedora-test                     # serial console (Ctrl+] to exit)
virsh edit fedora-test                        # edit the libvirt XML
virsh dumpxml fedora-test > fedora-test.xml   # back up the config
virsh net-list --all                          # libvirt networks


# virt-install — scripted VM creation from an ISO

sudo virt-install \
    --name fedora-test \
    --memory 4096 \
    --vcpus 4 \
    --disk size=40,format=qcow2 \
    --cdrom ~/Downloads/Fedora-Workstation-Live-x86_64-44.iso \
    --os-variant fedora44 \
    --graphics spice \
    --network network=default

# list known --os-variant values
osinfo-query os | grep -i fedora


# SNAPSHOTS — only on qcow2 disks, not raw

# external (preferred for production) — disk file shared, RAM separate.
virsh snapshot-create-as fedora-test pre-experiment \
    --description "before kernel test" --atomic
virsh snapshot-list fedora-test
virsh snapshot-revert fedora-test pre-experiment
virsh snapshot-delete fedora-test pre-experiment


# WINDOWS GUESTS — virtio drivers

# windows doesn't ship virtio drivers natively. install with the
# fedoraproject virtio-win ISO mounted as a second cdrom:
sudo dnf install virtio-win
ls /usr/share/virtio-win/                     # the ISO + per-driver dirs
# inside the windows installer, "load driver" → point at the virtio-win
# CD → pick viostor (storage) and netkvm (network).
# the spice-guest-tools msi installs everything else (clipboard, display
# resize, etc.).


# DISTROBOX / TOOLBOX — when you don't actually need a full VM

# toolbox is fedora's own (uses podman + fedora-toolbox image):
toolbox create -c f44-tools                   # default: matches host fedora
toolbox enter f44-tools
toolbox rm f44-tools

# distrobox is the more flexible tool — any distro image, with home /
# audio / x / wayland passthrough configured automatically:
sudo dnf install distrobox
distrobox create -n ubuntu24 -i docker.io/library/ubuntu:24.04
distrobox enter ubuntu24
distrobox list
distrobox rm ubuntu24

# common pattern: distrobox for "I want pacman / apt for this one
# task" without giving up your fedora host. the host's gpu, /home,
# and pulse/pipewire are already there.


# GPU PASSTHROUGH (advanced)

# single-GPU passthrough on linux is doable but messy (you give up the
# GPU to the VM and use a second one or ssh in). dual-GPU + IOMMU is
# the supportable path. the fedora wiki and arch wiki both have
# extensive guides — start there rather than improvising.
# preconditions: VT-d / AMD-Vi enabled in firmware, distinct iommu
# groups for the GPU, vfio-pci binding.
lscpu | grep -i 'virtualization'
dmesg | grep -i iommu                         # look for "IOMMU enabled"
ls /sys/kernel/iommu_groups/                  # one dir per group


# WHICH ONE SHOULD YOU INSTALL?
#
#   "i want to try this ISO"                 → gnome-boxes
#   "i want to run a windows VM long-term"   → virt-manager
#   "i want a reproducible dev env"          → distrobox, then vagrant
#   "i want to run apt for one task"         → distrobox / toolbox
#   "i want to script VM provisioning"       → virsh + virt-install
#   "i want browser-driven VM mgmt"          → cockpit-machines
#   "i want GPU passthrough"                 → virt-manager + reading


CONTAINERS — PODMAN FIRST
-------------------------

# fedora ships PODMAN as the blessed container engine, not docker.
# docker was removed from fedora repos in F31 (cgroups v2 conflict at
# the time; long since resolved, but red hat moved to podman). podman
# is daemonless and rootless-by-default — two real wins over docker on
# a personal machine:
#
#   - no `dockerd` running as root, no socket to secure, no `docker`
#     group with effective-root power.
#   - containers run as YOUR user via user namespaces. the classic
#     "added myself to the docker group and now my container can mount
#     /" escalation doesn't exist.
#
# podman's CLI is docker-compatible — every `docker <verb>` has a
# matching `podman <verb>`. most tutorials work verbatim.


# DAY-ONE INSTALL
sudo dnf install podman podman-compose podman-docker buildah skopeo
#   - podman           — the engine + CLI
#   - podman-compose   — python wrapper that reads docker-compose.yml
#   - podman-docker    — installs /usr/bin/docker as a symlink to podman
#                        so copy-pasted `docker ...` commands work
#   - buildah          — image builder (more flexible than `podman build`)
#   - skopeo           — inspect / copy images across registries without
#                        pulling them locally

# verify rootless works:
podman info | grep -iE 'rootless|graphRoot'
podman run --rm hello-world


# DAILY COMMANDS (docker-compatible)

podman run -it --rm -v "$PWD":/work fedora:44 bash   # one-off interactive
podman run -d --name web -p 8080:80 nginx           # detached, name + port
podman ps                                           # running containers
podman ps -a                                        # all (including stopped)
podman images                                       # local image cache
podman logs -f web                                  # follow container logs
podman exec -it web bash                            # shell into a container
podman stop web && podman rm web                    # stop + remove
podman rmi nginx                                    # remove an image
podman system prune -af                             # nuke unused (CAREFUL)


# BUILDING IMAGES

# from a Containerfile (or Dockerfile — podman accepts either name):
podman build -t myapp:dev .

# multi-arch build (useful with cross-platform deploys):
podman build --platform linux/amd64,linux/arm64 -t myapp:dev .

# buildah for fine-grained / scripted image construction:
buildah from fedora:44
# (returns a working container; modify it with `buildah run`, then
#  `buildah commit` to produce the image. cleaner than Containerfile
#  for highly-conditional builds.)


# COMPOSE — three options

# 1. podman-compose (python wrapper, simplest path):
podman-compose -f docker-compose.yml up -d

# 2. `podman compose` (subcommand, since 4.1) — finds podman-compose or
#    docker-compose and wraps it. one less command to remember:
podman compose up -d

# 3. QUADLET — podman's native systemd integration, no compose at all.
#    write a .container unit file in ~/.config/containers/systemd/
#    and systemd manages the lifecycle. cleanest path for long-running
#    services.

mkdir -p ~/.config/containers/systemd
cat >~/.config/containers/systemd/web.container <<'EOF'
[Unit]
Description=nginx via podman quadlet

[Container]
Image=docker.io/library/nginx:latest
PublishPort=8080:80
Volume=%h/www:/usr/share/nginx/html:Z

[Service]
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target
EOF
systemctl --user daemon-reload
systemctl --user enable --now web.service        # quadlet derives the unit name


# REGISTRIES — fedora's default search list

# podman searches multiple registries by default. config at
# /etc/containers/registries.conf — fedora preconfigures registry.fedoraproject.org,
# registry.access.redhat.com, docker.io, and quay.io. that's why bare
# image names (e.g. `nginx`) just work without the docker.io/ prefix.
podman search nginx                              # tries all configured registries

# disable a registry temporarily by using the fully-qualified name:
podman run docker.io/library/nginx               # explicit


# WHEN TO REACH FOR DOCKER INSTEAD

# - a workflow REQUIRES the docker daemon socket (testcontainers, some
#   IDE integrations, docker-in-docker CI runners that hard-code
#   `unix:///var/run/docker.sock`).
# - shared docker-compose.yml using docker-specific extensions you
#   can't change.
# - team / corp standardization on docker.
#
# install path (note: external repo, extra trust surface):
sudo dnf -y install dnf-plugins-core
sudo dnf config-manager addrepo --from-repofile=https://download.docker.com/linux/fedora/docker-ce.repo
sudo dnf install docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-buildx-plugin docker-compose-plugin
sudo systemctl enable --now docker
sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"      # log out and back in
# don't install both podman and docker as root daemons casually —
# they'll fight over /var/lib/cni and iptables rules. if you need
# both, run docker rootless or pick one.


# CONTAINER-AS-DEV-SHELL (covered in VMs section)

# distrobox and toolbox both run on podman. when you want "I need apt
# for this one task" without giving up your fedora host, use those
# rather than spinning up a long-lived podman container — they handle
# /home, GPU, audio, x/wayland passthrough for you.


# WHICH ONE FOR WHAT
#
#   "i want to run nginx as a service"        → podman + quadlet
#   "i want to follow a docker tutorial"      → podman + podman-docker
#   "i have a docker-compose.yml"             → podman-compose
#   "i need testcontainers / DinD CI"         → docker
#   "i want a long-lived dev environment"     → distrobox (see VMs)
#   "i want to build multi-arch images"       → podman build --platform
#   "i want to inspect a registry image"      → skopeo inspect


